246–1287","1228–Male":"1228–Deceased","1228":"1228","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1246":"1246","1334":"1334","1287":"1287","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Ham, Gloucestershire, England":"Ham, Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mortimer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Mortemer in Seine-Maritime, France, so called from Old French <i>mort(e)</i> ‘dead’ + <i>mer</i> ‘sea’, probably referring to a stagnant pond or drained swamp.","Irish (of Norman origin): the Norman surname in sense 1 above was taken to Ireland from England in the medieval period, where it has also been adopted by bearers of the Gaelic surnames <b>Mac Muircheartaigh</b> and <b>ÓMuircheartaigh</b>, commonly Anglicized as <b>McMurty</b> and <b>Mortagh</b>. Compare   McMurdo  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mortimore","meanings":["English (Devon; of Norman origin): variant of   Mortimer  ."]},{"name":"McMurdo","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Muircheartaigh</b> or <b>Mac Muircheartaich</b>, ‘son of Muircheartach’, a personal name meaning ‘sea-ruler’. In Scotland the name was often lenited to give   McCurdy  . Compare   Murdoch   and   Moriarty  . The name was also used to Anglicize <i>Mac Murchaidh</i> (see   McMorrow  )."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":11,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":42,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":67,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Hugh de Mortimer was born in 1248, in Ham, Gloucestershire, England as the son of Hugh Mortimer. He had at least 1 son with Sibyl de Braose."},"et":{"1248–":"1248–Surnud","1248–Male":"1248–Surnud","1248–1334":"1248–1334","1246–1287":"1246–1287","1228–Male":"1228–Surnud","1228":"1228","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1246":"1246","1334":"1334","1287":"1287","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Ham, Gloucestershire, England":"Ham, Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"1248–":"1248–Kuollut","1248–Male":"1248–Kuollut","1248–1334":"1248–1334","1246–1287":"1246–1287","1228–Male":"1228–Kuollut","1228":"1228","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1246":"1246","1334":"1334","1287":"1287","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Ham, Gloucestershire, England":"Ham, Gloucestershire, England"},"fr":{"1248–":"1248–Décédé","1248–Male":"1248–Décédé","1248–1334":"1248–1334","1246–1287":"1246–1287","1228–Male":"1228–Décédé","1228":"1228","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1246":"1246","1334":"1334","1287":"1287","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Ham, Gloucestershire, England":"Ham, Gloucestershire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Hugh de Mortimer est né en 1248, à Ham, Gloucestershire, Angleterre, fils de Hugh Mortimer. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Sibyl de Braose."},"de":{"1248–":"1248–Verstorben","1248–Male":"1248–Verstorben","1248–1334":"1248–1334","1246–1287":"1246–1287","1228–Male":"1228–Verstorben","1228":"1228","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1246":"1246","1334":"1334","1287":"1287","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Ham, Gloucestershire, England":"Ham, Gloucestershire, England","lifeSummary":"Hugh de Mortimer wurde 1248 in Ham, Gloucestershire, England, als Sohn von 